---
/*
 * Docs · Your icons — the flagship, case-by-case reference for the
 * automatic icon-data layer. Where the five Patterns pages document the
 * explicit `optical-center` directive (a marker you write), this page
 * documents what happens with NO directive at all: the Vite plugin finds
 * the icon SVG in your build graph by shape and bakes the perceptual
 * shift into the asset itself. One section per real-world icon source.
 *
 * Mental model the page establishes:
 *   - Reach the pixels at build time → corrected automatically, zero markup.
 *   - Can't reach them (runtime/remote/opaque component) → fall back to the
 *     container directive, which centers the slot. Never silent.
 */
import DocsLayout from "../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro";
import CodeBlock from "../../components/docs/CodeBlock.astro";

const toc = [
  { id: "promise", label: "One plugin, every icon", level: 2 as const },
  { id: "rule", label: "The one rule", level: 2 as const },
  { id: "matrix", label: "Compatibility at a glance", level: 2 as const },
  { id: "iconify", label: "Iconify", level: 2 as const },
  { id: "iconify-set", label: "A whole collection", level: 3 as const },
  { id: "iconify-single", label: "Single-icon modules", level: 3 as const },
  { id: "iconify-dynamic", label: "Dynamic icon names", level: 3 as const },
  { id: "svg-files", label: "Local SVG files", level: 2 as const },
  { id: "own", label: "Your own icon data", level: 2 as const },
  { id: "unplugin", label: "unplugin-icons", level: 2 as const },
  { id: "components", label: "Icon component libraries", level: 2 as const },
  { id: "runtime", label: "Runtime & remote icons", level: 2 as const },
  { id: "control", label: "Opt out & control", level: 2 as const },
  { id: "baked", label: "How the shift is baked in", level: 2 as const },
];
---

<DocsLayout
  title="Any icon library"
  description="Add the Vite plugin once. The icons you already import — Iconify, your own SVG files, unplugin-icons, a hand-rolled icon map — come out optically centered, with no per-icon work and nothing shipped to the browser."
  toc={toc}
>
  <h2 id="promise">One plugin, every icon</h2>
  <p>
    Every other page on this site documents the
    <code>optical-center</code> directive — a marker you write on a
    container or an <code>{`<svg>`}</code>. This page documents the
    opposite: the icons you <em>don't</em> mark. The Vite plugin reads
    your build graph, recognises icon SVG wherever it appears, and bakes
    the perceptual shift straight into the asset. You write your normal
    code.
  </p>

  <CodeBlock
    filename="vite.config.ts"
    lang="ts"
    code={`import { defineConfig } from 'vite';
import opticalCenter from 'optical-center/vite';
import react from '@vitejs/plugin-react';

export default defineConfig({
  // This line is the entire setup. Nothing else changes.
  plugins: [opticalCenter(), react()],
});`}
  />

  <p>
    No custom plugin to write, no precompute script, no committed offset
    file, no runtime library. The detection is by <strong>shape</strong>,
    not by package name — so a brand-new icon library, or one you built
    yourself this afternoon, is handled the same way as Iconify.
  </p>

  <h2 id="rule">The one rule</h2>
  <p>
    There is exactly one thing that decides whether an icon is corrected
    automatically:
  </p>
  <aside class="callout callout--tip">
    <p class="callout-label">The rule</p>
    <p>
      If the plugin can reach the icon's SVG <strong>at build time</strong>
      — as data, a string, or a file the bundler walks — it is corrected
      automatically. If the pixels only exist at runtime, it can't be
      (you can't optically centre what you can't measure), and you fall
      back to the container directive, which centres the slot.
    </p>
  </aside>
  <p>
    This is the natural boundary of a zero-runtime tool. Everything below
    is just that rule applied to the shapes icons actually ship in. When
    an icon can't be reached, the build prints a one-line summary saying
    so — it is never corrected silently and never skipped silently.
  </p>

  <h2 id="matrix">Compatibility at a glance</h2>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Where your icons come from</th>
        <th>What you write</th>
        <th>Correction</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td>Iconify offline — <code>@iconify/json</code> + <code>addCollection</code></td>
        <td>your normal import</td>
        <td>Automatic</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Iconify single-icon — <code>@iconify/icons-*</code></td>
        <td>your normal import</td>
        <td>Automatic</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Local <code>.svg</code> files — svgr, <code>?raw</code>, <code>?url</code></td>
        <td>your normal import</td>
        <td>Automatic</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Your own icon-data module</td>
        <td>your normal export</td>
        <td>Automatic</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>unplugin-icons — <code>~icons/*</code></td>
        <td>your normal import</td>
        <td>Automatic</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Hand-written inline <code>{`<svg>`}</code></td>
        <td><code>optical-center="auto"</code> on the svg</td>
        <td><a href="/docs/patterns/inline-svg">Directive</a></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Component libraries — lucide-react, react-icons, Heroicons</td>
        <td><code>optical-center: auto</code> on the wrapper</td>
        <td><a href="/docs">Directive</a></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Runtime / remote — <code>{`<img src>`}</code>, Iconify API</td>
        <td><code>optical-center: auto</code> on the wrapper</td>
        <td>Slot only</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>
    The first five rows are this page. The last three are the
    <a href="/docs">directive patterns</a> — reach for them when the
    pixels aren't reachable, or when you want to centre the slot rather
    than the asset.
  </p>

  <h2 id="iconify">Iconify</h2>
  <p>
    <a href="https://iconify.design">Iconify</a> is the common case, so
    it's first. Whether you register a whole collection or import one
    icon at a time, the geometry arrives as data — which is exactly what
    the plugin can read.
  </p>

  <h3 id="iconify-set">A whole collection</h3>
  <p>
    The idiomatic offline setup: import a set from
    <code>@iconify/json</code> and register it. You write this exactly as
    you would without optical-center.
  </p>
  <CodeBlock
    filename="icons.ts"
    lang="ts"
    code={`import { addCollection } from '@iconify/react';
import mdi from '@iconify/json/json/mdi.json';

addCollection(mdi);`}
  />
  <CodeBlock
    filename="HomeButton.tsx"
    lang="tsx"
    code={`import { Icon } from '@iconify/react';

export const HomeButton = () => (
  <button>
    <Icon icon="mdi:home" />
  </button>
);`}
  />
  <p>
    <strong>What happens:</strong> the plugin intercepts
    <code>mdi.json</code> as Vite loads it, recognises the Iconify
    collection shape, and bakes the per-icon shift into each icon body.
    <code>{`<Icon>`}</code> then renders the corrected geometry. Nothing
    runs in the browser — the JSON that reaches the bundle is already
    corrected.
  </p>
  <aside class="callout callout--note">
    <p class="callout-label">You chose "correct everything"</p>
    <p>
      Every icon in a registered collection is corrected, not just the
      ones whose names appear in your source. That's what makes the
      <a href="#iconify-dynamic">dynamic-name</a> case below work. The
      first cold build of a large set does the measuring work once and
      caches it on disk; later builds are instant.
    </p>
  </aside>

  <h3 id="iconify-single">Single-icon modules</h3>
  <p>
    Importing one icon at a time — the
    <code>@iconify/icons-*</code> packages — works the same way, and only
    the icons you actually import get measured.
  </p>
  <CodeBlock
    filename="HomeButton.tsx"
    lang="tsx"
    code={`import { Icon } from '@iconify/react';
import home from '@iconify/icons-mdi/home';

export const HomeButton = () => <Icon icon={home} />;`}
  />

  <h3 id="iconify-dynamic">Dynamic icon names</h3>
  <p>
    Because the whole registered set is corrected at build time, the icon
    name can be fully dynamic at runtime and still render centered — the
    case that defeats every static-analysis approach.
  </p>
  <CodeBlock
    filename="IconGrid.tsx"
    lang="tsx"
    code={`import { Icon } from '@iconify/react';

// \`name\` is unknown until runtime — still corrected, because the whole
// collection was baked at build time.
export const Cell = ({ name }: { name: string }) => (
  <Icon icon={\`mdi:\${name}\`} />
);`}
  />

  <h2 id="svg-files">Local SVG files</h2>
  <p>
    SVG files you import — as a
    <a href="https://react-svgr.com">svgr</a> component, as a raw string,
    or as a URL — are corrected at the source. The plugin runs before
    svgr compiles, so by the time your component (or your
    <code>?raw</code> string) exists, its <code>viewBox</code> already
    carries the shift.
  </p>
  <CodeBlock
    filename="Toolbar.tsx"
    lang="tsx"
    code={`import PlayIcon from './icons/play.svg';      // svgr → a React component
import rawStop from './icons/stop.svg?raw';     // the raw SVG string

export const Toolbar = () => (
  <>
    <PlayIcon />
    <span dangerouslySetInnerHTML={{ __html: rawStop }} />
  </>
);`}
  />
  <p>
    Works for a single file or a whole folder via
    <code>import.meta.glob</code>. Decorative artwork that happens to be
    an <code>.svg</code> — a logo, an illustration — can be
    <a href="#control">opted out</a> so it isn't nudged.
  </p>

  <h2 id="own">Your own icon data</h2>
  <p>
    The detection is structural, so a home-grown icon set — a plain
    module that maps names to SVG markup — is recognised with no
    adapter and no registration. This is the case that proves the plugin
    isn't tied to any one library: it has never heard of your module,
    and it works anyway.
  </p>
  <CodeBlock
    filename="my-icons.ts"
    lang="ts"
    code={`// Not Iconify. Not even JSON. Just your strings.
export const icons = {
  play: '<path d="M8 5v14l11-7z" />',
  stop: '<rect x="6" y="6" width="12" height="12" />',
  next: '<path d="M5 4l10 8-10 8V4zM17 4h2v16h-2z" />',
};`}
  />
  <p>
    <strong>What happens:</strong> the plugin parses the module's static
    export, sees string values that are SVG markup, and bakes the shift
    into each one. Because you own the source, this is the lowest-friction
    case of all — there's nothing to wire up.
  </p>

  <h2 id="unplugin">unplugin-icons</h2>
  <p>
    <a href="https://github.com/unplugin/unplugin-icons">unplugin-icons</a>
    serves icons through virtual <code>~icons/*</code> modules. The
    optical-center plugin sees the SVG those modules produce and corrects
    the <code>viewBox</code> before it reaches your component.
  </p>
  <CodeBlock
    filename="vite.config.ts"
    lang="ts"
    code={`import Icons from 'unplugin-icons/vite';
import opticalCenter from 'optical-center/vite';

export default defineConfig({
  // Order doesn't matter — optical-center corrects what unplugin emits.
  plugins: [opticalCenter(), Icons({ compiler: 'jsx' })],
});`}
  />
  <CodeBlock
    filename="Home.tsx"
    lang="tsx"
    code={`import IconHome from '~icons/mdi/home';

export const Home = () => <IconHome />;`}
  />

  <h2 id="components">Icon component libraries</h2>
  <p>
    Libraries like
    <a href="https://lucide.dev">lucide-react</a>, react-icons, and
    Heroicons don't ship icon <em>data</em> you import — they ship React
    components that draw the SVG when they render. There's no asset in
    the build graph to rewrite, so these use the
    <a href="/docs/patterns/jsx-attribute">directive</a>: mark the
    wrapper and the build centres the slot.
  </p>
  <CodeBlock
    filename="PlayButton.tsx"
    lang="tsx"
    code={`import { Play } from 'lucide-react';

export const PlayButton = () => (
  <button>
    <div optical-center="auto">
      <Play />
    </div>
  </button>
);`}
  />
  <p>
    Same end result, reached a different way — the icon lands on its
    optical centre instead of its bounding-box centre. See the
    <a href="/docs/patterns/css-class">CSS class</a> and
    <a href="/docs/patterns/tailwind">Tailwind</a> patterns for the
    CSS-side equivalents.
  </p>
  <aside class="callout callout--note">
    <p class="callout-label">Why not automatic?</p>
    <p>
      The geometry lives inside the component's render code, not in a
      file the bundler can rewrite. Rather than execute and re-serialise
      third-party components, optical-center leaves the markup to you and
      centres at the container — and the build summary lists any
      component-library icon it saw, so the gap is visible, not silent.
    </p>
  </aside>

  <h2 id="runtime">Runtime & remote icons</h2>
  <p>
    When the SVG only exists at runtime — fetched from the
    <a href="https://iconify.design/docs/api/">Iconify API</a>, loaded
    from a remote URL, or set as an
    <code>{`<img src>`}</code> — the build genuinely cannot see the
    pixels. There is nothing to measure, so the icon's own mass can't be
    corrected. The honest fallback is to centre the <em>slot</em> it sits
    in:
  </p>
  <CodeBlock
    filename="RemoteIcon.tsx"
    lang="tsx"
    code={`// styles.css
//   .icon-slot { optical-center: auto; }

export const RemoteIcon = ({ url }: { url: string }) => (
  <span className="icon-slot">
    <img src={url} alt="" />
  </span>
);`}
  />
  <p>
    This centres the box the icon occupies, which is the best a
    build-time tool can do without the pixels. The build summary flags
    these so you know which icons fell back to slot-centering.
  </p>

  <h2 id="control">Opt out & control</h2>
  <p>
    Automatic means automatic, but you stay in charge of the edges. To
    skip a specific asset — a logo, an illustration, an icon you've
    already hand-tuned — add the <code>?optical=off</code> query to its
    import:
  </p>
  <CodeBlock
    filename="Brand.tsx"
    lang="tsx"
    code={`import logo from './brand/logo.svg?optical=off&raw';`}
  />
  <p>
    To scope the whole pass — exclude a dependency, or narrow it to your
    own folders — pass <code>include</code> / <code>exclude</code> to the
    plugin:
  </p>
  <CodeBlock
    filename="vite.config.ts"
    lang="ts"
    code={`opticalCenter({
  // Default is "everything reachable". Narrow it if you need to.
  iconData: {
    exclude: ['**/brand/**', /node_modules\\/some-illustration-set/],
  },
});`}
  />

  <h2 id="baked">How the shift is baked in</h2>
  <p>
    Same model as everywhere else in optical-center — rasterise once,
    find the optical centre, ship a flat result — applied per icon at
    build time. Three details make it safe to do automatically:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Detected by shape, not name.</strong> A value is treated as
      an icon only if it carries SVG markup <em>and</em> corroborating
      geometry; payloads that merely happen to have a <code>body</code>
      field (HTTP responses, CMS records) are rejected. Anything
      ambiguous is left untouched.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Wrapped, not reshaped.</strong> The shift is applied as an
      inner <code>{`<g transform="translate(…)">`}</code> around the icon
      body rather than by editing its
      <code>left</code>/<code>top</code> fields. That's what lets a
      corrected Iconify icon still respond correctly to a runtime
      <code>hFlip</code> or <code>rotate</code> prop — the translate rides
      inside the renderer's own transform instead of being overwritten by
      it.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Measured once, cached on disk.</strong> Each unique icon
      body is rasterised a single time across your whole project and
      stored under <code>node_modules/.cache</code>. Repeat builds reuse
      it; identical icons shared across collections collapse to one
      measurement.
    </li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    In <code>vite build</code> the pass completes before anything is
    emitted, so production output is fully corrected and flat. In
    <code>vite dev</code> a large set is served immediately and corrected
    in the background, then hot-reloaded into place — the dev server
    never blocks while a collection is measured.
  </p>

  <aside class="callout callout--tip">
    <p class="callout-label">Roadmap</p>
    <p>
      The automatic icon-data layer is the build-time successor to the
      hand-written plugins people used to wire up for Iconify. It is
      additive to the stable <a href="/docs">directive patterns</a> — if
      you're already marking containers, nothing changes. See
      <a href="/docs/warnings">warning codes</a> for how the build
      reports anything it couldn't reach.
    </p>
  </aside>
</DocsLayout>
